			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">I avoid PvP because of grief players.  One of the reasons I quit EQ was because of being forced to deal with people who took the fun and relaxation out of the game for me.   I play NWN with my wife on our network now and quite enjoy the "carebear" atmoshphere.  I play computer games to relax and not to get wound up in competition. 
<br />

<br />
I play a lot of wargames by email and snail mail.  I've been doing this for about 20 years.  I suppose this is a kind of PvP environment because you are competing on a ladder against other people or teams.  I still enjoy it though because there is a feeling of sportsmanship and gentlemanly play.  I have yet to play against someone, who although could be very competative, plays for "grief."  In fact, even with the most competative, there tends to be a set of "gentlemens" rules that are widely agreed on.  Things like, don't assault armour with halftracks, don't use leaders without troops to complete an encirclement, don't sit on your opponents reinforcement locations, don't use trucks or bailed out crews offensively.  These are things that the game allows for but are unrealistic and "gamey."  Even the most competative players avoid doing things like this.  For them the win is important but the integrity of the play is more important.
<br />

<br />
I think part of the difference with wargames is there is a punishment for being a dink.  Like real life, if you're a dink you get ostrasized and run out of people to play with.  A smaller venue perhaps, word gets around.
<br />

<br />
I have nothing against PvP.  For some folks it's the cat's ass.  And they're welcome to it.  I like my cup of tea and a nice carebear rpg with my wife.
