				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">I read that article, and I was laughing pretty hard at those two idiots by the end of it.
<br />

<br />
"All PvP has been ruined since someone got PK'd in UO and told someone else about it who decided they didn't like it". What a crock.
<br />

<br />
PvP is not innately the problem. The people who PvP are. Unfortunately, people are much more clever than the computer code could ever be, and so keeping 'tardboys like the author and his "interview" subject in check requires either massive artificial restrictions, or direct supervision by another human brain.
<br />

<br />
I notice how they are filled with complaints about how other systems work, while basically offering no idea of their own except that because of the IPY shard, PvP could be really successful. It isn't hard to find 8500 people out of 20+ million (a conservative estimate) who share your ideas.
<br />

<br />
Of course PvP works on smaller scales with tabletop wargames, or Warcraft III, or Counterstrike, because it's right there in the definition: Smaller scale. It's quite easy to monitor the actions of a handful of people. It's easier for the other players to get to know a handful of people. The same thing simply does not apply when expanded out to a playing population of 3000, with 10,000 more subscribers who just aren't online at the time. Also, there are no accounts with multiple characters to hide behind in smaller scenarios. One of the problems with the penalties ascribed to PKs in UO (and which could be easily used in any other game, since there is no practical way to stop it) was that they could own a house, have 2 characters with the key, the PK drops off the loot, and the clean-as-a-whistle second character scoops it up, without ever having the slightest chance of his name being connected with the PK side. You'd need to restrict accounts to a single character (or have the actions of one character affect all characters on the account), and ban people from owning multiple accounts. How feasible does that really seem?
<br />

<br />
The article is opinionated, biased claptrap. They start with the base assumption that everyone wants to PvP...given that this assumption is patently false, it takes the foundation out of the whole arguement, and the rest of the bullshit falls down like the house of cards it is.<span class="gensmall"></span>


