			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">PvP was not very balanced when it was inroduced to EQ the game was designed PvE. At least thats where the balancing was stressed overwhelmingly pre-release.  Rogues were sick and were stripped very hard and were a bastard class for a LONG time.  Part of the unblanace was in PvE.
<br />

<br />
Here's my view on that incident and how it illustrates several difficulties in having PvE and PvP mix.  In the game they wanted to create a melee DPS that could not take hits but could deliver extreme and accurate hits the rogue was an obvious choice.  The balance was hard to keep though especially in PvP.  It did not matter what your AC was. Deliver enough damage fast enough and you win.
<br />

<br />
You should be able to do it. Old tried and true strategy games have high damage unts with low defense.  They did a pretty good job getting it right from a theoretical point of view.  There were complications though especially in PvP.
<br />

<br />
They wanted to make the class play like a classic rogue with hiding and sneaking not to mention backstabbing and pickpocketing.  This was something that in my opinon was very well done in EQ.  They matched the classes to their classic game functions very well.  In PvP though, mixing the skills and the melee was just too much.  Invisiblity was not weighted enough in PvE as it needed to be in PvP forget the gross sudden death damage.
<br />

<br />
What EQ wanted to rely on in their Vision (TM used without knowlege or permission of the owner) was that social balance would make random killing socially unacceptable.  It makes sense that there would be sneaky people that could assasinate you if you gave them reason.  Also, it should behoove you, if you have enemies, to travel with groups of people that can cast see invis.
<br />

<br />
EQ was socially designed as well. Characters were supposed to have to depend on each other. However, the interface did not at all support communities well.  People could kill you anonymously with trains. You would only know if you were lucky enough to see the SoB.
<br />

<br />
Guild management was impossible and almost seemed to be broken to encourage loot vultures. How many years did it take for them to give guildmembers the abilty to check a live roster?  You still cannot get a log of invites and removals.  If there is political strife in leadership, and an officer struck back to insult or is a mole from a rival unscrupulous guild... Yeash.  They can deliver massive social damage to large amounts of people.
<br />

<br />
Factor in not being able to tie an account to one person.  EBay and multi-boxing were balance comlications on their own.  in gameplay and socially they magnified the problems in social/gameplay balance exponentially.
<br />

<br />
Bind spot camping and naked casters were good illustrations of more complexities, that demanded social reprecussion in PvP.  Had rogues not been nerfed, they would have been right in there.
<br />

<br />
What can you do?  You sure can not allow people to trace accounts to live people.  "Sniper caught. Shot man over arguement in Bastion of Thunder. Are your children safe? News at 11."  Heck you would suffer major backlash if you even tried to ID users vs registration internally.  Some states actually have laws about that sort of thing that come into play when you do that sort of check on peoples lives and homes.
<br />

<br />
You cannot tell a parent that he cannot let his 8 year old play a character on his account.  Not and get away with it. Brothers?  Husband and wife?  Forget it.  To track and proove who is who? Impossible.<span class="gensmall"></span>


				</div></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
